Overview

Everything is a game: Assessing the use of gamified components in neurofeedback tools

with a self-care and productivity BCI application

Kyle Cordez

PSYCH 403: Neuroimaging and Neurostimulation

Kyle Mathewson

December 16, 2025

---

Everything is a Game

Games are everywhere. The interactive and competitive nature of games, particularly video

games, create an engaging, motivated experience. We might employ techniques or procedures

similar to gaming mechanics to accelerate productivity by defining an objective and rewarding

the completion of tasks. Furthermore, already we find gamification in what we do in our

day-to-day life, such as products we interact with and already have. In fact, in an economy that

seeks to capture as many people‚Äôs attention as possible, gamification is very common.

Everyday ‚ÄúGames‚Äù

As I review a few examples, let‚Äôs consider how we identify gamification in a product.

Multiple sources reference a set of ‚Äúformal game elements‚Äù to lay out the groundwork for game

design (e.x., Game Design Toolkit, n.d.; LeBlanc, 2020) that outline similar if not virtually the

same features, which can be identified to have drawn from Tracy Fullerton‚Äôs Game Design

Workshop: A Playcentric Approach to Creating Innovative Games (2004) and Ian Schreiber‚Äôs

Game Design Concepts course (2009). These elements include:

‚óè The player and that which they play the game through interaction with.

‚óè Objective or objectives that the player is attempting to achieve.

‚óè Rules or mechanics that lay out the actions that are allowed within the game.

‚óè Procedures or sequencing involves the actions the player takes to progress the game.

‚óè Resources can be used by the player to progress the game.

‚óè Conflicts or obstacles create resistance to progress.

---

‚óè Boundaries separate the game from everything else that isn‚Äôt the game. This can overlap

with rules.

When considering how apps and other programs employ these game elements, it is

important to recognize that some elements, particularly the objectives and conflicts, are already

defined by the purpose of the app or program.

Rewards and points loyalty programs

Starbucks , Tim Hortons , and other food and coffee chains have apps that employ a points

system where every purchase gives the customer points. Then, these points can be redeemed for

later purchases. The mechanics and sequencing involves purchasing, scanning, and redeeming.

The objective would be to get better deals. Your resources are the app itself, and the points. The

boundaries are that you can only use your resources for the company that created it. This also

includes e-commerce businesses like Amazon , apparel companies, and more.

Dating apps

It seems even love is a game. The rules or mechanics of a dating app define how you are

able to choose who to interact with. A user‚Äôs resources are their own attractive attributes, or the

features of the app that allow them to display these. The objective: find love.

Language learning and other game-based learning

Duolingo is one such learning mobile application that uses gamified mechanics. The

objective is to master the language, but there are others that include maintaining a daily streak or

rising up a leaderboard in competition with other users. Procedures are in the lessons. The

---

resources are the app‚Äôs learning materials. Using such elements can further incentivize learning,

making it more engaging for learners.

Self-care and productivity apps

There are a number of apps that use gamified elements for self-care and productivity. For

example, Finch: Self-Care Pet is a self-care and habit-tracking app where the procedures or

sequencing for progression takes the form of taking care of a fictional bird. Checking of self-care

tasks and healthy habits promote this digital bird‚Äôs growth, as well as provide currency to design

its home. Habitica is a to-do list app that focuses on habit-tracking and productivity using RPG

elements. It has a mechanic that allows bad habits to hurt the player character, but allows them

recovery.

I will outline a rough, barebones design for a simple self-care and productivity app that

uses gamified mechanics and neurofeedback to enhance user experience. I will also design an

experiment that measures the effectiveness of this app, namely the gamified aspects of it. In other

words, this paper outlines a specific method that could be used to potentially examine the effects

of employing gamification on correlates, particularly on productivity and neural correlates such

as stress and attention over time. My primary objective is to open the discussion for the active

and considerate use of game elements in neurofeedback technology. Is gamification actually

effective? From a clinical or research perspective, what impact does it have on people?

---

BCI App Design: SPACE MISSION ‚Äî Self-care and

Productivity App

Space Mission is a self-care and productivity to-do list app with a gamified interface. It uses

neurofeedback (EEG-acquired brain signals) to help the user handle self-care, train focus, and

learn methods to return to a calm state from a stressed one. The design of this app draws heavy

inspirations from existing habits, self-care, and productivity apps, especially the aforementioned

Finch and Habitica . It is also intended to contain specific meditation and breathing exercises that

can be properly included with research.

Inspired by my submitted midterm assignment, the engaging aesthetic theming of the app

is space travel. By checking off items in their self-care habits list (‚Äúself-maintenance‚Äù tasks or

SM tasks) and to-do list (‚Äúduty and operations‚Äù tasks or DO tasks), they are managing and

driving a fictional ship through space.

---

User Interface Sketch

---

Screen A: SM tasks

This is a scrollable tab where the user can look at, complete, and tick off self-care and

good habits tasks. Some task items always appear on the list everyday, while others can appear

randomly each day. These task items are pre-generated, including to-do‚Äôs such as:

‚óè ‚ÄúMake your bed‚Äù

---

‚óè ‚ÄúBrush your teeth‚Äù

‚óè ‚ÄúMeditate‚Äù

‚óè ‚ÄúComplete a breathing exercise‚Äù

‚óè ‚ÄúTake a walk‚Äù

‚óè ‚ÄúTake a 5-10 minute screen-free break‚Äù

‚óè ‚ÄúClean your workspace‚Äù

‚óè ‚ÄúJournal your emotions‚Äù

Some tasks, like the last of the examples, can prompt the user to write a short diary entry

if desired. Each task item have five central properties:

‚óè Name: The name is the visible property that identifies the task ( ‚Äúmake your bed‚Äù ).

‚óè Ticks: The ticks of a task item starts at 0 everyday when the user hasn‚Äôt completed the

task. When the user ticks it/checks it off once, this property increments by 1.

‚óè Completed today , {true, false}: Each task is taken off the board (will not be generated on

the list) when it has been completed on a given day (completed today == true).

‚óè Daily, {true, false}: Task items with property daily set to true will always appear

everyday. Those set to false may or may not appear randomly on the board as extra tasks

to do for the day.

‚óè Difficulty, {easy, effortful}:

‚óè Parts: This refers to how many times a user may tick off a task item in a day, starting

from 1 for most items (e.x., ‚Äúbrush your teeth [0/2] ‚Äù ). A task item will only be completed

today when it has been ticked by the user the same number of times as the parts.

All task items are reset to not completed today and ticks = 0 at the beginning of each day.

---

If the user is wearing the paired EEG device, neurofeedback can suggest tasks with easy

difficulty by adding them to the board when stress is detected. The app can also send a

notification to remind the user to complete an easy self-care task. These settings can be

customized and changed by the user (e.x., turn notifications off).

Some task items might also have a property I will refer to as Focus . Tasks such as

meditate , complete a breathing exercise , and take a walk give the user an option to enter a visual

and/or auditory timed neurofeedback session (may be instructed in the case of a meditation or

breathing exercise session) intended to be used during the task completion. Naturally, in order to

get neurofeedback, the user will have to be wearing the paired EEG device for the session. This

session takes the user to a different screen that locks them out of using other parts of the app until

the session has been completed.

A focus session includes visual and auditory feedback. With space sounds

accompaniment, the ship will appear to move speedily through stars when beta waves are high

and slow down when alpha waves are high.

The number of tasks that the user adds on this to-do list and completes are tracked to

gauge productivity.

Screen B: DO tasks

This is another scrollable tab consisting of a to-do list that is fully customizable by the

user. Users can enter their productivity tasks under this tab. Each created task item has the

following properties that the user can edit:

‚óè Name

‚óè Ticks

---

‚óè Completed , {true, false}

‚óè Repeat, {none, daily, weekly, bi-weekly, monthly}: A task that is set to ‚Äònone‚Äô for repeat

will be permanently taken off the board once completed.

‚óè Difficulty: {easy, medium, effortful}

‚óè Parts

‚óè Due date: If applicable, the user can set a due date for the task and they will be notified

for its completion.

Every task item also has an option for the user to enter a focus session, similar to what

was described above. Like for SM tasks, the number of tasks that the user adds on this to-do list

and completes are tracked to gauge productivity.

Screen C: Charts

Similar to the visuals in focus sessions, the ship will fly faster past colourful stars when

beta waves are high, and slow down through calmer regions of space when alpha waves are high.

When the user scrolls down on this page, they will be able to see their beta, alpha, and theta

waves displayed in wave form.

These are only active when the user is wearing the connectable EEG device. Otherwise,

the ship will simply be moving at a fixed, neutral speed and the waves are flat.

More Implementations

The features outlined above are the central pieces, but to further ‚Äúgamify‚Äù the application

and potentially increase engagement with the game aspects in turn, more mechanics may be

added.

---

‚óè Customizable astronaut character and spaceship: some tasks might give coins to allow the

user to be able to buy cosmetics from a shop (hats, toolboxes, wallpapers, etc.) to change

the appearance of the app.

‚óè Progress bar: as the user ticks off more tasks, a progress bar can be filled similar to

‚Äúlevelling up‚Äù in video games.

‚óè Space discoveries: in addition to the progress bar, we can implement discoveries of

planets and stars every time the user hits a milestone.

Paired EEG Device

The device uses EEG, and is non-invasive. We might improve the BCI‚Äôs neurofeedback,

especially when we want to be able to differentiate when the user is focused or stressed. Similar

to some Muse devices, PPG sensors might be integrated to track blood pressure or heart rate. A

multimodal approach can also be taken, using both EEG and fNIRS for greater precision, namely

improved spatial and temporal resolution where each individual modality lacks. Additionally,

for these specific neuroimaging applications, strain for the user is minimal especially in contrast

with other modalities. They are also energy efficient (Chen et al., 2024). This is advantageous as

it allows comfortable use of the app in tasks requiring attention, or for self-maintenance habits

like meditation. Pairing these technologies with the detection of brain waves would improve

insights from neurofeedback data. This is also great for decreasing strains and costs for

collecting laboratory or clinical data about the user‚Äôs brain activity.

Formal classification between focus and stress levels will be further explored in the

outline of the experimental design.

---

Rough Experimental Design

For this study, full-time or part-time university students (aged 18-25) will be used as a sample.

University students can be not only an accessible sample but an effective sample choice to track

alertness coupled with productivity, as we can use a semester as the time period for our

longitudinal study. They will be randomly assigned to the experimental group and the control

group.

‚óè Experimental group: using the app.

‚óè Control group: not using the app, but they will be provided with the same EEG portable

devices being used for the app and a less robust application that will contain a simple,

straightforward to-do list feature and record alertness and stress over time without

gamified mechanics .

Both groups will be asked to use their EEG devices at least once a week throughout the

semester, during study/deep-focus work sessions. The point is to be able to compare attention

levels, stress levels, and productivity over time between the experimental (gamified) group and

the control group. Both groups are encouraged to add to and use their to-do lists regularly and

truthfully, twice a week at the minimum to be able to collect evidence for productivity, as the app

can save ticked-off to-do list item history.

---

Phase 1: Training and Learning

Training the BCI‚Äôs classification algorithm

For the app to track both attention and stress as well as respond to these two distinct

states requires being able to differentiate between them after they have been preprocessed. A

classification algorithm should be implemented to the BCI application to feed training data to.

We cannot rely solely on live neurofeedback training data during the use of the app to fully train

the classification algorithm, so I propose the use of offline training data pre-study. Participants‚Äô

EEG brain wave data are collected and preprocessed, while they complete continuous

performance tasks live in a lab for attention classification. For pre-study tests, attention tasks will

be used to engage participant focus. We might use continuous performance tasks (CPTs). The

CPT paradigm requires the participant to direct their attention to an indicated target stimulus

amongst a continuous stream of stimuli. They are required to respond or withhold their response

when they detect this target (Roebuck et al., 2017). Performance on such tests can be a gauge of

an individual‚Äôs attention, particularly sustained and selective attention for CPTs. This will also be

used in post-study assessments.

Classification techniques are used to be able to assess mental stress or mental focus, after

signal acquisition followed by feature extraction. Once we have the necessary data from our

EEG modality and filtered out the noise, we classify the different brain patterns. There are

methods for this process. For example, convolutional neural networks (CNNs) take in a

multidimensional input and process it through multiple layers, primarily suited for image inputs

(O‚ÄôShea & Nash, 2015). In a review by Badr and colleagues that put a focus on CNNs along with

long short-term memory networks (Badr et al., 2024), the algorithms used was not only

---

considered but as well as factors that impact their effectiveness, such as whether the data is raw

or presented as manipulated images and feeding more information by having greater variability

in experimental conditions. To illustrate how we would make the decision here: if our BCI

produces images especially in the multimodal EEG-fNIRS approach, CNNs might be a stronger

option.

Phase 2: Gamification of Productivity

Again, the study follows the participants over the course of the semester.

What we are looking for

‚óè Attention and stress levels at the beginning of the study, before the app has been used.

‚óè Attention and stress levels after the study.

Productivity will also be noted. It will be measured by participant interaction with the

to-do list, but a questionnaire will be administered at the end of the study. The questionnaire will

ask participants to answer questions relating to how consistent they have been with coursework,

with an example of a specific question being ‚ÄúOn average, how many hours do you spend

studying everyday?‚Äù

---

Reflections and Remarks

What would conducting experiments tell us? Namely, we want to look at the differences in

attention and stress levels at the beginning of the experiment and after. If the experimental group

who is utilizing the gamified elements of the app show an enhancement in attention, then we

might consider that the app has helped them improve. No differences at all does not answer our

research question. It would be worth including a history of average daily or weekly brain wave

recordings to monitor specific changes over time, which would add computational costs in the

production of the app.

Limitations and Set-backs

Costs to Run Experiment and Costs for Using App

There would be some concerns for what the costs would be for the distribution of the

EEG devices to the participants. Making compromises in the sample size might be necessary to

reduce cost, which raises concerns for the internal validity of the experiment. We must also

consider the computational costs of collecting training data for the classification system.

Participation and User Engagement

We can be limited by the amount of actual participation we get from the sample. IWe

cannot always guarantee consistent use of the app. Ways to secure participation can include

making the game more engaging or, again, considering the participants‚Äô well-being with rewards

and constant check-ins.

---

Generalizability

To some extent, we are able to contribute to the discussion of how the use of gaming

elements are linked to neural correlates. This experimental design is specifically designed for the

rough application design, which in part I have marketed as a means to gauge the effectiveness of

gamification on attention, stress, and productivity while using neurofeedback from BCI

applications to measure these.

Questions of more specific points of study can be drawn from the concerns expressed

about user engagement and participation in the previous section. We can further split

experimental groups into participants who get a version of the game with more video game

elements, such as customizability as discussed earlier and perhaps quests like those we see in

Finch . Are more video games elements more effective, or should we minimize this? How

productive is allowing user freedom and customizability in these products? From a marketing

standpoint, it certainly is, if it boosts user engagement. But can we expect greater benefits on the

user side, such as improvements in attention?

Other studies have explored this already, which we can review to make predictions about

potential results. One study (Wang et al., 2025) had their experimental group use the

neurofeedback game Mindflex during physical education university classes. Unlike the control

group, the experimental group showed boosts in performances of attention in post-test scores.

---

Overall, the purposes of these designs are as follows:

1. To tell us whether the app has positive neural effects on users: if we measure attention

and stress levels over time during the course of the usage of this app, will we see positive

results?

2. To tell us whether the app can be used as a diagnostic tool or a way for medical

professionals and researchers to track users‚Äô alertness?
